    <h1>Commerce with Mathematics:</h1>

    <p>Chartered Accountant (CA): A highly respected profession in finance and accounting. CAs handle auditing, taxation, financial reporting, and advisory services for businesses and individuals.
    </p>

    <p>Company Secretary (CS): CS professionals ensure compliance with corporate laws and regulations. They manage board meetings, maintain corporate records, and advise on legal and governance matters.</p>

    <p>Cost and Management Accountant (CMA): CMAs focus on cost management, budgeting, and financial planning within organizations. They analyze costs, develop strategies, and provide insights for decision-making.</p>

    <p>Actuarial Science: Actuaries assess financial risks in insurance, pensions, and investments. They use mathematical and statistical models to analyze data and make predictions about future events.</p>

    <p>Financial Analyst: Financial analysts evaluate investment opportunities, analyze financial data, and provide recommendations to investors, companies, or financial institutions.</p>

    <p>Banking and Finance: Students can pursue careers in banking, investment banking, financial planning, wealth management, or corporate finance roles.</p>

    <p>Management Consulting: Management consultants advise organizations on improving performance, efficiency, and strategy. They analyze business processes, identify opportunities, and provide recommendations for improvement.</p>

    <p>Data Analytics and Business Intelligence: With strong mathematical skills, commerce graduates can work in data analytics, market research, business intelligence, or data science roles.</p>

    <h1>Commerce without Mathematics:</h1>
    <p>Bachelor of Commerce (B.Com): Graduates can pursue general B.Com degrees and specialize in areas such as Accounting, Finance, Marketing, Human Resources, or International Business.</p>

    <p>Bachelor of Business Administration (BBA): BBA programs offer a broad understanding of business principles, management practices, and organizational behavior.
    </p>
    <p>Retail Management: Students can specialize in retail management and pursue careers in retail operations, merchandising, store management, or e-commerce.</p>

    <p>Human Resource Management (HRM): HR professionals manage employee recruitment, training, performance evaluation, compensation, and organizational development.</p>

    <p>Marketing and Sales: Graduates can work in marketing, advertising, sales, brand management, market research, or digital marketing roles.</p>

    <p>Event Management: Event planners organize and execute events such as conferences, exhibitions, weddings, and corporate events.
    </p>
    <p>Hospitality Management: Students can specialize in hospitality management and pursue careers in hotels, resorts, restaurants, event venues, or tourism agencies.</p>

    <p>Public Relations (PR): PR professionals manage communication between organizations and their stakeholders, including media relations, crisis management, and brand promotion.</p>

